# Layer dependencies

CSVI is layered. Dependencies flow **downward only** — never upward or sideways across peers.

```
common → (no internal deps)
io     → common
layout → common, io (types only where needed)
nav    → layout/types only — pure logic, no UI
cmd    → common — no UI, no app state
ui     → common, layout — ncurses stays here
app    → all lower layers — orchestration only
bin    → app, common — CLI parsing only
```

## Forbidden includes

| Module | Must NOT include |
|--------|------------------|
| `common/` | any other `src/lib/*` header |
| `io/` | `ui/`, `nav/`, `app/`, `cmd/` |
| `layout/` | `ui/`, `nav/`, `app/`, `cmd/` |
| `nav/` | `ui/`, `app/`, `cmd/` |
| `cmd/` | `ui/`, `app/`, `nav/` |
| `ui/` | `app/`, `cmd/` |

## Hard boundaries

- Only `src/bin/main.c` may parse `argv` or call `getopt_long`.
- Only `src/lib/ui/` may `#include <curses.h>`.
- `nav/` and `cmd/` stay pure — no ncurses, no viewer state.

If a change requires breaking these rules, extract shared logic into a lower layer first.
